Mª Dolores Merat Onorato

Este REA está dirigido al alumnado de 4.º y 5.º de Educación Primaria en la asignatura de Educación Artística (Música), en su modalidad bilingüe (inglés).
El recurso tiene como objetivo que el alumnado conozca a la mítica banda Queen, los instrumentos que tocaban, las notas musicales y los silencios, y que practique el ritmo de algunas de sus canciones más conocidas mediante la percusión con palos de madera (u otras alternativas, según las necesidades del alumnado). Además, se fomenta el uso de la lengua extranjera para comparar, describir y exponer información de forma oral y escrita.
La tarea final consiste en una presentación oral sobre lo aprendido acerca de la banda, seguida de un mini concierto de percusión en el que deberán poner en práctica ritmos, compases, y la duración de notas y silencios.

QUEEN: A LEGENDARY BAND

Queen was an English rock band formed in 1970. They are considered one of the best rock bands in recent history, with thousands of fans all over the world. They recorded several best-selling albums. They broke up in 1982.

MEMBERS OF THE GROUP

The members of the band are Freddie Mercury, Brian May, John Deacon, and Roger Taylor.

Freddie Mercury was the leader of the band, singer and songwriter. He formed Queen in 1970 with Brian May and Roger Taylor.

He wrote numerous hits for Queen, such us "Bohemian Rhapsody", "Somebody to Love", "Don't Stop Me Now" and "We Are the Champions”

Brian May was born in 1947. He was the guitarist of the rock band.

John Deacon was the bass guitarist and songwriter for the band. He composed several singles for the group including "Another One Bites the Dust" and "I Want to Break Free".

Roger Taylor was the drummer and songwriter of the legendary band.

Beats, bars and metres

A beat is the regular sound in music.

Beats go in groups. A group of beats is called bar.

On the musical lines, a bar is between two vertical lines.

Each bar has a number of beats.

Metre is how we count the beats in each bar. It tells us the rhythm.

- A duple metre has 2 beats in each bar.

- A triple metre has 3 beats in each bar.

Musical symbols and beats

In music, we have different notes.

Each note has:

– a name

– a symbol

– a rest (silence)

– a number of beats


Whole note and rest

It is the longest note.

It looks like a circle.

The rest is a rectangle under the line.

It has 4 beats.

Half note and rest

It looks like a circle with a stick.

The rest is a rectangle on top of the line.

It has 2 beats.

Quarter note and rest

It looks like a black circle with a stick.

The rest looks like a zigzag.

It has 1 beat.

Eighth note and rest

It has one flag.

The rest is a small curve.

It has 1/2 beats.

Sixteenth note and rest

It has two flags.

The rest has two small curves.

It has 1/4 beats.

Descripción

Este REA está dirigido al alumnado de 4.º y 5.º de Educación Primaria en la asignatura de Educación Artística (Música), en su modalidad bilingüe (inglés).

El recurso tiene como objetivo que el alumnado conozca a la mítica banda Queen, los instrumentos que tocaban, las notas musicales y los silencios, y que practique el ritmo de algunas de sus canciones más conocidas mediante la percusión con palos de madera (u otras alternativas, según las necesidades del alumnado). Además, se fomenta el uso de la lengua extranjera para comparar, describir y exponer información de forma oral y escrita.

La tarea final consiste en una presentación oral sobre lo aprendido acerca de la banda, seguida de un mini concierto de percusión en el que deberán poner en práctica ritmos, compases, y la duración de notas y silencios.

This OER (Open Educational Resource) is aimed at 4th and 5th grade Primary Education students in the subject of Arts Education (Music), in its bilingual (English) modality.

The objective of the resource is for students to learn about the legendary band Queen, the instruments they played, musical notes and rests, and to practice the rhythm of some of their most well-known songs using wooden sticks for percussion (or other alternatives, depending on students' needs). In addition, the use of the foreign language is encouraged to compare, describe, and present information both orally and in writing.

The final task consists of an oral presentation about what they have learned about the band, followed by a mini percussion concert in which they will put into practice rhythms, time signatures, and the duration of notes and rests.
